      • getObjectClass

        public String getObjectClass()
        LDAP object class used to represent this schema object during LDAP operations.

        More specifically, this value creates a mapping from the entity to an LDAP object class. That object class will be used in LDAP operations for deciding how to structure and interpret this entity's data.

      • getNamingKey

        public String getNamingKey()
        Attribute name that appears in the LDAP entry's leftmost RDN.

        An LDAP entry's leftmost RDN is a name-value pair where the name and value are separated by an equals (=) sign, for example `cn=George Washington`. This method returns the name portion (or left side) of the RDN, such as "cn".

        This value will often correspond to one of the entry's attributes, such as cn, givenName, username, etc. However, IDDM administrators can customize this value.

      • getNamingAttributes

        @NonNull
public @NonNull List<String> getNamingAttributes()
        Names of the attributes used to construct the LDAP entry's leftmost RDN value.

        An LDAP entry's leftmost RDN is a name-value pair where the name and value are separated by an equals (=) sign, for example `cn=George Washington`. This method returns the names of the attributes used to construct the value (or right side) of the RDN.

        This list will often contain only one entry, such as ["cn"] when only the `cn` attribute value appears in the RDN. But additional attributes can be included to build more complex RDN values.

      • getAdditionalDisplayAttributes

        @NonNull
public @NonNull List<String> getAdditionalDisplayAttributes()
        Names of attributes used to customize the LDAP entry's displayed RDN.

        An LDAP entry's leftmost RDN is a name-value pair where the name and value are separated by an equals (=) sign, for example `cn=George Washington`. IDDM support customizing the value (or right side) by prepending additional attributes values. This method returns the names of the attributes used to customize the RDN value.

        For example, if the cn=George Washington entry includes attributes title=President and politicalParty=Independent, then the RDN might be customized such that this method returns ["politicalParty", "title"] to constructor the RDN cn=Independent President {George Washington}.
